07/06/2009
CHISINAU, Moldova -- Turkey assumed the year-long presidency of the Southeast Europe Co-operation Process (SEECP) from current presidency holder, Moldova, at a summit in Chisinau on Friday (June 5th). Addressing fellow heads of state, Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan said stability in the Balkans will be a priority as it is "a prerequisite for peace and security in Europe". He also urged NATO and the EU to keep their doors open to Balkan countries to encourage continued reforms. Bulgarian President Georgi Parvanov, his Serbian counterpart Boris Tadic and Macedonian Foreign Minister Antonio Milososki also attended the summit. (Tanjug, B92 - 06/06/09; MIA, BNR, Anadolu news agency - 05/06/09)
